The Perl driver's MongoDB::OID should fail gracefully, i.e. return a value that cannot be matched against any valid record, if the supplied value to the new constructor is not valid.

Example:
{noformat}$db->get_collection('test')->find({_id => MongoDB::OID->new(value => '506b37b1a7e2037c1f000449')});{noformat}
- Returns 'test' document with _id: ObjectId("506b37b1a7e2037c1f000449");

{noformat}$db->get_collection('test')->find({_id => MongoDB::OID->new(value => '506b37b1a7e2037c1f0004')});{noformat}
- Returns 'test' document with _id: ObjectId("506b37b1a7e2037c1f000400");
- MongoDB::OID->new should have failed and no records returned.

In MongoDB Shell, properly handled:
{noformat}
> db.test.find({_id: ObjectId("506b37b1a7e2037c1f0004")});
Wed Dec  5 01:36:38 Assertion: 10448:invalid object id: length
Wed Dec  5 01:36:38 Error: 10448 invalid object id: length (shell):1
{noformat}
